   <text>
       <body>
           <lg>
               <l> Sitting where a graceful rimo <note>Rimo. A species of conifer distinguished by its drooping branches and patterned bark.</note></l>
               <l> By the riverside, I listened </l>
               <l> Unto what the waters said. </l>
           </lg>
           <lg>
               <l> Through a mighty rift beneath me </l>
               <l> Swift the roaring torrent whirled, </l>
               <l> And within its rocky channel </l>
               <l> Whitely in the sunbeams curled; </l>
           </lg>
           <lg>
               <l> Leaping, dancing, brightly glancing, </l>
               <l> As it wound its course along,</l>
               <l> This appeared unto my fancy </l>
               <l> Something like the river’s song: </l>
           </lg>
           <lg>
               <l> "Ever swiftly I am hasting </l>
               <l> “Onward, onward to the sea, </l>
               <l> “And toward the great FOR-EVER </l>
               <l> “Life as swiftly beareth thee; </l>
           </lg>
           <lg>
               <l> “Soon into that mighty ocean </l>
               <l> “Will thy little life be cast, </l>
               <l> “Hurry, hurry, mortal hurry, </l>
               <l> “Labor hard, and labor fast.” </l>
           </lg>
       </body>
   </text>      
